---
import BaseLayout from "../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import FlavorTabs from "../../../components/FlavorTabs.astro";
import ModuleHero from "../../../components/module/ModuleHero.astro";
import ModuleFooterNav from "../../../components/module/ModuleFooterNav.astro";
import ModuleQuiz from "../../../components/module/ModuleQuiz.astro";
import { flavor as gcp } from "../../../data/flavors/gcp";
import { flavor as aws } from "../../../data/flavors/aws";
import { flavor as azure } from "../../../data/flavors/azure";
import { flavor as oss } from "../../../data/flavors/oss";

const moduleId = "75-finops";
const entries = {
  gcp: gcp[moduleId],
  aws: aws[moduleId],
  azure: azure[moduleId],
  oss: oss[moduleId],
};
---

<BaseLayout title="75 · FinOps for GenAI">
  <article>
    <ModuleHero moduleId={moduleId}>
      <p>
        Module 55 gave every request a trace with token counts attached. FinOps is where that data finally earns its
        keep: turning a monthly bill into $/query and $/tenant numbers you can act on, instead of a total that only
        goes up.
      </p>
    </ModuleHero>

    <h2>Unit economics: $/query and $/tenant</h2>
    <p>
      Joining the Module 55 event log against your cloud's billing export, per request, gets you real unit economics:
      cost per query, and — grouped by tenant — cost per tenant. That second number is what lets you answer "is this
      customer profitable at their usage volume" instead of just "did total spend go up this month."
    </p>

    <h2>Where the money actually goes</h2>
    <p>
      It's tempting to assume the vector index or the embedding calls are the expensive part, since they touch every
      document. In practice, LLM <strong>output tokens</strong> usually dominate: embeddings are computed once per
      chunk and priced far lower per token, while every generation call produces new output tokens priced at a
      premium. Confirming this with your own event-log join, rather than assuming it, tells you where to actually
      spend optimization effort.
    </p>

    <h2>Semantic caching and model routing</h2>
    <p>
      Two changes move the needle without touching answer quality. <strong>Semantic caching</strong> matches a new
      query against previously answered ones — not just exact repeats — so rephrased or repeated questions skip the
      expensive generation call entirely. <strong>Model routing</strong> sends every query to a fast, cheap model
      first, and escalates to a reasoning-tier model only when retrieval confidence is low or the fast model itself
      signals uncertainty — the same fast-first pattern Module 25 introduced for serving, now applied deliberately for
      cost.
    </p>

    <h2>Prompt caching: a different mechanism, a bigger discount</h2>
    <p>
      Semantic caching skips the call entirely for a repeated <em>question</em>. <strong>Prompt caching</strong> is
      narrower but fires far more often: every provider now lets you cache a repeated <em>prefix</em> of the
      prompt — the system prompt, the retrieved chunks, the tool definitions — so only the new part (the user's
      actual question) gets processed at full price. The discount is consistently steep across providers:
      Anthropic bills cache reads at <strong>10% of the base input price</strong> — a
      <a href="https://platform.claude.com/docs/en/build-with-claude/prompt-caching" target="_blank" rel="noopener">90% discount</a>
      — with a 5-minute or 1-hour TTL; <a href="https://aws.amazon.com/bedrock/prompt-caching/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Bedrock's
      prompt caching</a> matches that ~90% cut for Claude and Nova models via explicit cache checkpoints (minimum
      1,024–4,096 tokens depending on model); OpenAI and Azure OpenAI
      <a href="https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/guides/prompt-caching" target="_blank" rel="noopener">apply caching automatically</a>
      to repeated prefixes with zero code changes; and
      <a href="https://cloud.google.com/blog/products/ai-machine-learning/vertex-ai-context-caching" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Vertex
      AI's context caching</a> bills cached tokens at roughly 10% of standard input price, with a small hourly
      storage fee on top. The practical move: put your stable system prompt and retrieved context first in the
      request and your variable question last — that ordering is what makes the prefix cacheable at all.
    </p>

    <h2>Private inference: when self-hosting beats per-token pricing</h2>
    <p>
      A GPU sitting under a self-hosted model costs the same per hour whether it serves one query or ten thousand,
      which flips the economics compared to per-token API pricing. The way to compare them honestly: divide the
      GPU's hourly rate by its sustained tokens/sec throughput to get an effective $/token floor, then compare that
      against the API price for an equivalent model. In practice that break-even point sits at meaningfully high,
      steady volume — real-world estimates put it around single-digit-millions of tokens per month against a cheap
      API, and that's before counting the engineering and on-call time to keep a serving stack healthy, which often
      dwarfs the GPU bill itself at low-to-moderate volume. Below that volume, per-token API pricing usually wins
      even before factoring in ops cost. vLLM's own
      <a href="https://docs.vllm.ai/en/stable/features/automatic_prefix_caching/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">automatic
      prefix caching</a> (<code>enable_prefix_caching</code>) gets you the same repeated-context speedup as
      hosted prompt caching, at no extra charge, if you do end up self-hosting.
    </p>

    <h2>Capacity planning</h2>
    <p>
      Once volume is predictable, pay-as-you-go pricing stops being the cheapest option — a provisioned or reserved
      capacity commitment trades a fixed cost for a lower marginal rate. Capacity planning is the exercise of using
      your unit-economics data to find the volume at which that trade starts to make sense, instead of guessing.
    </p>

    <h2>Try it in your flavor</h2>
    <FlavorTabs moduleId={moduleId} entries={entries} />

    <h2>Pitfalls</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Optimizing embedding costs first because they "run for every document," when output tokens are usually the larger line item.</li>
      <li>Adding a cache keyed on exact query text only, missing the much larger set of semantically repeated questions.</li>
      <li>Routing every query to the reasoning-tier model "to be safe," which quietly multiplies cost for queries the fast tier would have handled fine.</li>
      <li>Committing to reserved capacity before volume is predictable, locking in a fixed cost that ends up more expensive than pay-as-you-go.</li>
      <li>Putting the variable part of the prompt (the user's question) before the stable part (system prompt, retrieved context) — that ordering makes nothing cacheable, so prompt caching's ~90% discount never fires.</li>
      <li>Comparing self-hosted GPU cost against API pricing using only the sticker price per hour, without counting the engineering/on-call time to keep a serving stack healthy — that overhead is often the larger number at low-to-moderate volume.</li>
    </ul>
  </article>
  <ModuleQuiz moduleId={moduleId} />
  <ModuleFooterNav moduleId={moduleId} />
</BaseLayout>
